canonical:
  title: 謝御衣酒箋
  author: 李詹
  language: lzh
  text: 恩如河海之深自天有命身乏絲毫之報無地可容恭惟性禀聦明道全仁智發號施令令出惟行崇德報功功疑惟重何圖睿睠濫及孱身特宣密勿之言兼致殊尤之錫玉壺中鵝黃酒忽千里之春風寶藏裏狐白裘眞一朝之佳貺旣優承於宣勸玆反顧以自銘臣謹當每輸華祝之誠保獻嵩呼之筭
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝御衣酒箋
  author: 李詹
  language: lzh
  text: 恩如河海之深。自天有命。身乏絲毫之報。無地可容。恭惟性禀聦明。道全仁智。發號施令。令出惟行。崇德報功。功疑惟重。何圖睿睠。濫及孱身。特宣密勿之言。兼致殊尤之錫。玉壺中鵝黃酒。忽千里之春風。寶藏裏狐白裘。眞一朝之佳貺。旣優承於宣勸。玆反顧以自銘。臣謹當每輸華祝之誠。保獻嵩呼之筭。
korean:
  title: 의복과 술을 내린 데 대해 사례하는 글
  author: 이첨
  language: kor
  text: 은혜가 하해같이 깊어 하늘로부터 명이 내리시었는데 몸에는 털끝만한 보답할 것도 없으니 용납할 땅이 없습니다.공경히 생각하건대 전하께서는 성품은 총명을 탔고, 도(道)는 인지(仁智)를 겸하여, 호령을 내리시면 즉시 행해지고, 덕 있는 이를 높이며 공 있는 이를 갚아주되, 공이 의심되면 오직 후한 편을 취하였습니다. 돌보아주시는 은혜가 과람하게 하찮은 신의 몸에 미칠 줄 어찌 알았겠습니까. 친밀한 말씀을 내리고 겸하여 특수한 물품을 보내시니, 옥 항아리 가운데 아황주(鵝黃酒)는 갑자기 천리의 봄바람이요, 보배 상자에 호백구(狐白裘)는 참으로 하루아침의 아름다운 선물이라, 이미 권장함을 받았으니, 이에 스스로 돌아보고 명심하옵니다.신이 삼가, 언제나 화봉인(華封人)의 축하를 마땅히 드리고 숭산(嵩山)에서 부르던 수(壽)를 드리겠습니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0410_010_0100&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 호백구(狐白裘) : '
    value: 여우의 겨드랑이에 있는 흰털의 부분만을 모아서 갖옷[裘]을 만든 것이다.
english:
  title: A Letter of Gratitude for the Imperial Gift of Wine and Robes
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your grace flows deep as rivers and seas, descended from the mandate of Heaven itself. Yet my meager form offers not even a thread's worth of return—there is no earth that could contain my shame.

    I humbly reflect that Your Majesty's nature is endowed with brilliance, your Way perfected in both benevolence and wisdom. When you issue commands, they are obeyed in an instant. You elevate the virtuous and reward the faithful, and when merit seems uncertain, you err always on the side of generosity. How could I have imagined that your benevolent gaze would fall upon one so insignificant as myself? Yet you have spoken words of intimate favor and bestowed upon me treasures most precious.

    The golden wine in its jade vessel comes like the spring breeze traveling a thousand leagues. The white fox fur in its precious casket—truly it is the gift of a single blessed morning. Having already received such encouragement, I turn inward now and engrave this upon my heart.

    I solemnly vow to offer always the sincere blessings of the Sage of Hua, and to present the longevity chants sung upon sacred Mount Song.
  footnotes:
    - The 'golden wine' (鵝黃酒) refers to a precious imperial liquor with a golden-yellow hue, symbolizing the warmth of imperial favor.
    - The 'white fox fur' (狐白裘) is made from the silvery-white hair from the underarms of foxes—an extremely rare and valuable luxury item in imperial China.
    - The 'Sage of Hua' and 'Mount Song' are classical allusions to virtuous figures and sacred locations, used here to express the writer's wish for the ruler's longevity and continued virtue.
